node.text:
In March, @AirbnbExperiences hosts all over the world had to stop doing what they love—sharing their interests and passions with others. 
Over the past few weeks, they’ve offered ideas for how to continue hosting even while we’re apart. 
They’ve adapted recipes based on what’s in their pantries, turned living rooms into yoga studios, and choreographed dances for families at home.

Today we’re excited to announce that Airbnb Experiences are now online. You can take a flamenco class with Lidón in Madrid, participate in a tarot card reading with Mak in Austin, or visit a colony of penguins in Cape Town—all from home.

True to Airbnb Experiences in real life, Online Experiences are hosted by remarkable people and set in small groups. Alongside making a new dish, maybe you’ll make a new friend, too.

Thank you to our incredible hosts around the world. We’ll see you online soon —> link in bio.

node.text:
Can a desert wildflower superbloom take the form of a house? This colorful getaway says, emphatically, yes. Float the day away in your saltwater pool, play some croquet on your lawn, or head out for famous date shakes from Windmill Market.

Link in bio to answer in the affirmative. 

Photos: @yesyesyeshouse

spell "YES".

A close up of the round white table and 3 orange chairs. There is a yellow bowl with lemons and a modern light hanging from the ceiling. The wall is painted in a bright mural of shades of blue and green with a framed yellow picture that says "yes" 6 times.
A brightly colored kitchen with a white round table with 4 orange chairs, 4 yellow barstools against a turquoise tiled island. Out the window is a pool and big yellow letter that say "YES".
Photo by Airbnb in Clinton, Washington. May be an image of tree and outdoors.

node.text:
Douglas firs lift Max and Tatiana’s treehouse to one of the highest points on Whidbey Island. Once you’ve settled in, hike through the woods down to Possession Beach, stopping for blackberries along the way. (But save room for dinner at Orchard Kitchen, straight from island farms and the Salish Sea.) 

Link in bio for handmade hideaway.

Photo: @treehousewhidbey

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Airbnb in Trancoso, Bahia, Brazil. May be an image of tree, outdoors and pool.

node.text:
This spacious villa puts you and a dozen or so of your favorite people close to both the white-sand Praia dos Coqueiros and the Quadrado, the welcoming village green at the heart of town. Save one evening for pineapple lobster at Capim Santo. 

Link in bio for bohemian beach town.

Photo: @casadycampo and @living.trancoso

node.accessibility_caption: A two story a-frame villa surrounded by lush green foilage.

node.text:
Morning at Superhost Raj’s flourishing refuge starts with herbal tea straight from your garden. Maybe later you can pick some avocados for guacamole, feed the fish in the ponds, or walk to the deep green Bhimtal Lake and kayak to the island in the middle.

Link in bio for lush life.

Photo: @avocadosbnb

node.accessibility_caption: The view from a beach bungalow looking out to two other straw a-frame shaped bungalows surrounded by green plants along a gravel path.

node.text:
Superhost Alberto’s jungle bungalows are 150 meters from a beach with consistent waves and a range of breaks to suit just about any ability level. Even if you don’t surf, it’s impossible not to soak up the peaceful vibe (and you probably will surf by the time you leave).

Link in bio for hummingbirds and glassy barrels. 

Photo: @buena_onda_bungalows_

node.accessibility_caption: Close up shot of aqua water in a modern pool.

node.text:
Family trips inspired Giannis to create the kind of elegant yet kid-friendly place he’d rarely found. This villa  delivers on both fronts, with a pool that has a separate shallow end, plus bunks, books, and toys smartly tucked away among all the clean lines. Best of all, Analipsi Beach is a short walk away, even for the littlest legs. 

Link in bio for family chic.

Photo: @nayavillas

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Airbnb in São Miguel dos Milagres. May be an image of tree and outdoors.

node.text:
This rustic, palm-surrounded bungalow is close to so much pristine coastline that you can explore a different stretch of it every day. So it means a lot that guests save their highest praise not for the secluded beaches but for Luca and Marina, the welcoming and generous hosts. 

Link in bio for mangoes and manatees.

Photo: @obrabrasilia

When a bubble bath under banana plants isn’t the most relaxing part of your day, you’ve found a truly special place. Far from the crowds of town, this peaceful villa is a hundred steps from a pristine beach.

Link in bio to surf and soak. 

Video: @bellaangeles

node.text:
Natalia turns salsa making into a joyful dance, sometimes literally. Join her online in her Mexico City kitchen for a hands-on, highly musical master class. You’ll make three different authentic salsas, but you won’t just be learning recipes—you’ll be absorbing an approach to salsa that’ll last a lifetime. Warning: after your first perfectly charred tomatillo, you’ll never go back to the jar.

Link in bio to turn up the heat.

Photos: @mexicansalsas and @snackingkitchen

A white cave wall in Greece with a window open to the Ammoudi Bay in Santorini. The water is a bright crystal blue and fades to a mediterranean blue with a dock, boat, and caldera in the view. There is a clear vase in the window seal and a wooden chair in front.

node.text:
This cave house is not only steps away from Amoudi Bay, but also (more) steps up the stone stairway to the center of Oia. You might find yourself spending more time at sea level, though—a swimming cove and sailboat departure points are a short walk away.

Link in bio for sea breezes away from the crowds.

Photo: @nicolettahouses

Deep in the Hundred Acre Wood, there was a house fit for a bear. In honor of @pooh’s 95th anniversary, Disney appointed illustrator (and your Host) Kim Raymond curated a house sweet enough for Winnie the Pooh. Explore A.A. Milne’s wholesome world by snacking on hunny-infused meals, playing games of Poohsticks and exploring Ashdown Forest, the area that inspired the books 95 years ago.

UK residents can request to book this beary sweet stay on September 20 at 2pm BST. Link in bio.

node.text:
Superhosts Rich and Shannon lovingly restored this 1880s house on the edge of old town. When you feel like wandering, start with a strong local roast from Square One. To stick with the historical theme at night, book a lane at Decades, the vintage bowling alley and arcade just around the corner. 

Link in bio for Pennsylvania Dutch Country home base.

Photo: @thesarahbhoffman
